<DOC><DOCNO> AP880720-0056 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0353EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r p PM-CVN--ConventionBriefs     07-20 0557</FIRST><SECOND>PM-CVN--Convention Briefs,520</SECOND><HEAD>Few Notes of `Dixie' Greet Delegates Before Music Is Shut Off</HEAD><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A top official of the Democratic NationalConvention went quickly into action when delegates entering TheOmni arena were greeted by strains of ``Dixie.''   ``I gotta go,'' Don Fowler, chief executive officer of theconvention, told party chairman Paul Kirk when the taped musicstarted playing Tuesday. After unsuccessfully trying to signal thesound technician about 80 feet away, Fowler picked up an in-housetelephone and called him.   The song is considered offensive by some people who believe itrepresents the racism of the Old South.</TEXT><HEAD>Wrong Fight Song Greets Michigan Governor</HEAD><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Michigan Gov. James Blanchard was the victim of amusical faux pas when he prepared to address Democratic NationalConvention delegates about the party's campaign platform.   While Blanchard was being introduced Tuesday, the conventionband swung into a loudly enthusiastic rendition of ``The Victors,''the famed University of Michigan fight song.   Blanchard didn't wince, but there was a slightly painedexpression on his face. Blanchard is a devoted fan of archrivalMichigan State University.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Jerry Brown Hints At Future Bid For Office</HEAD><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Former California Gov. Jerry Brown says he mayrun for the U.S. Senate in 1992, but the former presidentialaspirant is currently helping his sister run for California statetreasurer.   Brown, 50, said Tuesday that ``it's possible'' he might run forthe Senate if Democrat Alan Cranston retires, but he has nospecific plans. Asked if he might run for governor again, hereplied: ``You shouldn't un-expect it.''   Brown made a brief appearance before the California delegationto the Democratic National Convention to help launch the 1990campaign for state treasurer of his sister, Kathleen.</TEXT><HEAD>LaRouche Addresses Maine Delegation</HEAD><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Political extremist Lyndon LaRouche spoke beforethe Maine delegation and left after receiving little response fromthe caucus. ``They let him talk and get it out,'' said delegateBill Meserve.   LaRouche warned delegates that ``America's headed for anotherdepression,'' Meserve said after LaRouche's presentation Tuesday.   Another member described it as ``a very mild speech _ mild forhim.''   Maine delegate John Martin, speaker of the state House ofRepresentatives, said he knew of no other appearances by LaRouche.   ``Other states just flatly refused to let him speak, but we'reopen, and he came and he spoke and he left,'' Martin said.</TEXT><HEAD>Billy Graham Says Robertson Should Have Remained a Minister</HEAD><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Rev. Billy Graham cited Jesse Jackson and PatRobertson as examples of how members of the clergy should andshould not campaign for public office.   Jackson's presidential candidacy has demonstrated that clergymencan seek public office and take strong moral stands withoutmingling religion with politics, Graham said Tuesday.   On the other hand, he said: ``If Pat Robertson made a majormistake, it was when he renounced his ordination. I think even thepeople who followed him, or people who didn't follow him, wouldhave a hard time understanding how a man could be called of God,ordained of God _ and you're ordained for life _ and to renounceit.''   Robertson made an unsuccessful bid for the Republicanpresidential nomination. Graham, who says he's not taking sides,delivered the invocation at Tuesday's session of the DemocraticNational Convention.</TEXT></DOC>